item.title: Its over
item.dc:creator: @lothy Lothy
item.description:
@lothy wrote:

[quote=“srt8, post:52, topic:241447”]Step one: Proposal written into a bill.

2: Bill introduced to one of the two houses of Congress.

3: Bill assigned to appropriate committee for debate.

4: If recommended favorably, the bill is read to the entire house of Congress (Senate or House of Representatives) for debate.

5: If it is passed, the bill goes to the other chamber of Congress.

6: If the bill passes, but amendments change the wording so different versions pass in the House and the Senate, the bill goes to conference committee to iron out those differences.

7: The revised bill is voted on by both chambers.

8: The bill is then submitted to the president, who can sign it into law or veto it.

  1. If the president vetos a law 2/3 of legislative branch can over rule it and still make it a law[/quote]
    That’s almost synonymous with the creation of Statute law in Australia. The only difference is that we have Parliament instead of Congress, and a Governor General signs off on the Bill to make it law instead of a President.

That said, presuming anti-gun legislation was introduced into Congress, it would have no greater chance of being passed than it would have with any other person introducing it, right? Just because the president wants something doesn’t mean that it gets to jump those steps you listed, and I’m sure the men and women that Congress is comprised of are as conservative as they’ve always been.

EDIT: Fixed a few errors.
